05282nam a22008415i 9789048540259DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20202020ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485402597 a10.1515/97890485402592doi  a(DE-B1597)548935  a(OCoLC)1154764213  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aDF505.7.P7 7aHIS0160002bisacsh04a949.5/013072022231 aStewart, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMasculinity, Identity, and Power Politics in the Age of Justinian :bA Study of Procopius /cMichael Stewart. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (246 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSocial worlds of late antiquity and the early Middle Ages ;v400tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Abbreviations -- tAcknowledgements -- tA Note on Translations, Sources, and Names -- tPreface -- tPart I. Finding Procopius -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Will the Real Procopius Please Stand Up -- tPart II. The Contest -- t3. The Danger of the Soft Life -- t4. Courage, Fear, and Generalship in the Vandal War -- t5. Shattering the Glass Ceiling: Eunuchs in a Changing World -- tPart III. Chaos Encroaching -- tIntroduction -- t6. Killing Justinian -- t7. Totila: Hero or Trope? -- tConclusion: All Quiet on the Italian Front -- tBibliography -- tChronology -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA generation of historians has been captivated by the notorious views on gender found in the mid-sixth century Secret History by the Byzantine historian Procopius of Caesarea. Yet the notable but subtler ways in which gender coloured Procopius' most significant work, the Wars, have received far less attention. This monograph examines how gender shaped the presentation of not only key personalities such as the seminal power-couples Theodora/ Justinian and Antonina/ Belisarius, but also the Persians, Vandals, Goths, Eastern Romans, and Italo-Romans, in both the Wars and the Secret History. By analysing the purpose and rationale behind Procopius' gendered depictions and ethnicizing worldview, this investigation unpicks his knotty agenda. Despite Procopius's reliance on classical antecedents, the gendered discourse that undergirds both texts under investigation must be understood within the broader context of contemporary political debates at a time when control of Italy and North Africa from Constantinople was contested.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aHistorianszGreece. 4aGender Studies. 4aHistory. 4aLate Antiquity. 4aLiterary History and Criticism. 7aHISTORY / Historiography.2bisacsh  aGender, Late Antiquity, Byzantium, Procopius, History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311068955608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2z978311069629508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPP ROW Ebook Package English 2020z978311069630140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048540259zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048540259423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789048540259.jpg  a978-3-11-068955-6  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-069629-5